  Updated thoughts on LDoN</span><hr size=1> Just a few random thoughts:<br>
<br>
1.  Things I don't like:  I still don't like the timed aspect of these adventures; if a group wants to grind away at an adventure until they succeed, I think the extra time it will take them is penalty enough, no need to deny them any points in addition.  The level limits are also annoying in that they limit who you can adventure with; it would be nice to be able to do these with a different mix of people (although changing this probably wouldn't help much without also changing the time limits so that there would still be a decent chance of success).<br>
<br>
2.  Things I do like:  The way they've implemented the leaderboard makes me not mind it; unless you are in the top 100, you don't show up on it, so my concerns about people using it to discriminate against different folks isn't actually an issue.  In fact, it is a nice incentive to grind away at these.  =)  As far as the adventures themselves go, the xp and loot have been great so far, and I'm drooling over some of the nicer buyable stuff in the camps.<br>
<br>
3.  Armor sets:  There are apparently different armor sets at each camp that can be bought with various amounts of points; the sets have a range of stats, recommended levels and points to buy.  There is plate class armor in the BB camp that goes for 760 points per piece that appears comparable to the armor from ornate molds, except instead of the nice effects on ornate you get empty slots that will cost more points to fill.  Apparently there are also sets of armor that go for 1492 points per piece; while afaik no one has posted the stats on that set for the plate armor, I'd expect it to be comparable to the armor from the elemental molds.  As someone who never really expects to see the elemental planes, I can't tell you how excited I am to have a new path to seriously upgrade my armor.  It will take a TON of grinding: a full set of the &quot;tier 6 armor&quot; would run 12,000 adventure points, plus god knows how many to fill the slots, buy stuff for other slots, new weapon, etc..  Even doing 10 successful adventures per week (not an unreasonable goal to sustain over the long term), it would take 6 months just to complete the basic set.  So I hope folks understand why I'm spending so much time there.  =)<br>
<br>
4.  I think LDoN has been and will be significantly easier for people who are level 60+.  The dungeons seem to be tuned for a well-balanced group of people in average gear.  As people level up, there can be some twinkage, but generally different people of a certain level are roughly the same in terms of overall power.  At level 65, however, people stop leveling and start pouring xp into AA, which the dungeons apparently don't account for.  I've grouped with several people who have 200+ AAs (which is sick, I know, I almost cried the first time someone in my group said &quot;ding 264&quot; or whatever absurd number it was), and for better or worse they are much more powerful than someone who just dinged 65 with no AAs completed.  Add to that the fact that many of the people I'm seeing in LDoN have gear from places I'll probably never see, and some of the adventures I've been on have been insanely easy.  And then there's also the fact that you get more points at higher levels (51 points on normal setting for success at level 65).  Someone like me who is level 65 but has average to sub-par gear and not many AAs can get an easy 51 points by just being the 6th man in a group of people who will just destroy one of these zones.<br>
